The '''Djerassi Resident Artists Program''' is an [[artist residency|artists]] and writers residency in [[Woodside, California]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://fineart.about.com/od/Artists-Residencies/p/The-Djerassi-Resident-Artists-Program-Artist-in-Residence.htm|last=Kendzulak|first=Susan| title=Fine Art: The Djerassi Artists Residency|publisher=[[About.com]]}}</ref> Sitting on a 583-acre ranch with a 12-sided cattle barn converted into artist studios.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://www.eastbaytimes.com/2007/07/28/djerassi-artists-retreat-hosts-rare-open-house/|title=Djerassi artists’ retreat hosts rare open house|date=2007-07-28|website=East Bay Times|access-date=2017-08-02}}</ref>
== History == It was co-founded in 1979 by [[Carl Djerassi]], the inventor of the [[Combined oral contraceptive pill|birth control pill]], and [[Diane Middlebrook]]. The residency is competitive and held at no cost to the artists. The location was a former cattle ranch. Originally a women's residency program, to honor his late daughter Pamela<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/10/12/travel/want-to-get-into-an-artists-retreat-go-as-a-tourist.html|title=Want to Get Into an Artists’ Retreat? Go as a Tourist|last=Tan|first=Cheryl Lu-lien|date=2014-10-10|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-08-02|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=":0" /> but later expanded to welcome all genders.
This residency offers a public open house event once a year.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ww2.kqed.org/arts/2015/07/22/arts-residency-programs-the-secret-engine-of-the-bay-area-arts-scene/|title=Arts Residency Programs: The Secret Engine of the Bay Area Arts Scene|work=KQED Arts|access-date=2017-08-02|language=en-us}}</ref>
